<section class="presentation hentry">
  <div class="page-area">

    <div class="title-wrap">

      <h1 class="title" title="Hardware Trends — Hardware by the Numbers">Hardware Trends — Hardware by the Numbers</h1>
    </div>

    <div class="author-sidebar with-author">
      <div class="narrative-holder">
        <div class="narrative-contents narrative"></div>
      </div>
      <h4 class="vcard author-box">
        <a class="author name fn" href="/noUpside" rel="author" title="Renee DiResta">
          <img alt="" class="avatar" src="https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/458807679352193024/1rj3ogYS.jpeg" />
          Renee DiResta
</a>          <span class="username">@noUpside</span>
      </h4>

      <img alt="Hardware Trends — Hardware by the Numbers" class="talk-thumb hidden" src="https://dcw2aol3p8ym3.cloudfront.net//app/public/media/thumbs/talks/medium/1f67a2857ce8ba9445d7cea0f327cbae02bf1f98.png?1409945235" />
    </div>

        <div class="viewport">

      <div class="loading">
        <strong class="presentate delay-children-animation"><b>P</b><b>r</b><b>e</b><b>s</b><b>e</b><b>n</b><b>t</b><b>a</b><b>t</b><b>e</b></strong>
      </div>

      <div id="talk-vybw2g">

          <!-- slide 1 -->
          <article id="slide-Xw74KX">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	Hi, I’m Renee DiResta, Principal at O’Reilly AlphaTech Ventures.
</p>
<p>
	Today I’m going to walk you through some of the interesting trends happening in hardware.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 2 -->
          <article id="slide-y0BJrX">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 Hardware is Hard. Everyone in this room has heard that phrase repeated over and over again. It gets a little bit old, but at the same time, it's true.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 3 -->
          <article id="slide-g4xDjg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	   "Hardware" is not any one thing. In startup land, it's a catchall for "that which is not just software.” VCs don't say "I invest in software," they say "I invest in SaaS”, mobile, social, local... you name it. There's specificity in software.
</p>
<p>
	The fact that we still talk about hardware as a monolithic category is indicative of how new the space still is.
</p>
<p>
	  So this talk aims to do break the hardware sector into component parts. We’re going to walk through the trends driving the hardware renaissance, and then delve into the sectors that investors and consumers care about.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 4 -->
          <article id="slide-g6WKjX">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 It used to be really difficult to start a hardware company. You could bring a product to market with the help of an agency, but if you were one guy in a garage, you had a long uphill battle.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 5 -->
          <article id="slide-yL7eqz">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	    And then the internet happened, and it was easier to discover others with similar interests. If you've ever seen Chris Anderson tell the founding story of 3D Robotics, he talks about creating a Ning community around UAVs and discovering other people who were as passionate about drones as he was. Online communities led to offline communities through directory sites like Hackerspaces.org and Meetup.com. The graph above shows the number of new hackerspaces being started each year. Some are small, others are large. Some are hardware only, some are software + hw, some are software only. Shared workspaces and Fab Labs turned DIY into DIWO.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 6 -->
          <article id="slide-grWZRX">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	The movement is global. Every continent except Antarctica is represented.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 7 -->
          <article id="slide-zKbapX">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	   And every state. Getting specifically into US trends, California leads the pack with 68 planned or existing hackerspaces (across all types), but each state has one, and more are being added every month.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://hackerspaces.org/wiki/List_of_ALL_hackerspaces" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 8 -->
          <article id="slide-ga06by">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 Concurrently, the Maker movement began to grow. By 2011, the mainstream press began to take notice: Wired magazine put Limor Fried on the cover of their August 2011 issue and called it “Big DIY: The Year The Maker Movement Broke”. Make Magazine and Maker Faire deserve a hat tip for bringing “hacking the real world” to mainstream audiences and providing a stage for people to share their work.
</p>
<p>
	  It’s inspired millions.
</p>
<p>
	 Since 2006, Maker Faire attendance has steadily grown, and the number of faires has increased. 2013 was the Year of 100 Maker Faires.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://makezine.com/2014/01/01/the-year-of-100-maker-faires/" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 9 -->
          <article id="slide-znKMwy">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	  Of course, Maker and hacker activity isn’t the same as hardware startup activity. To see those trends, we look at Meetup groups attended by founders and aspirational founders. Within the US, there is now a hardware startup meetup in almost every state.
</p>
<p>
	  The San Francisco Hardware Startup Meetup is perhaps the most active. Started by Nick Pinkston in 2011, it’s grown from 100 members to over 3000. The number of founders who want to build hardware companies is increasing.
</p>
<p>
	 [<a href="http://www.nickpinkston.com/2013/07/hardware-is-going-exponential-a-few-data-points.html" rel="nofollow">source</a>, updated data provided by Nick Pinkston via personal email]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 10 -->
          <article id="slide-zqYA2z">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 And over the past three years, support structures have emerged to support these founders. Each of the accelerators above operates slightly differently, taking in companies at various stages in the development process.
</p>
<p>
	 Some, like Bolt and Lab IX, act like extremely active seed funds. But all share the mission of helping hardware companies successfully bring a product to market.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 11 -->
          <article id="slide-gBbZpg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	There’s also a blossoming support ecosystem for the business side of things. The widespread consumer adoption of e-commerce provides hardware startups with a plausible alternative to getting onto the shelves of big-box.
</p>
<p>
	Logistics and fulfillment as a service companies help round out the direct-to-consumer ecosystem.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 12 -->
          <article id="slide-yPexeg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 Of course, all the business support in the world means nothing if you can’t produce the tech.
</p>
<p>
	 It’s easier than ever to get from an idea  to putting a product in the hands of consumers. Starting with prototyping – advances in rapid prototyping tools have made it far easier to construct a form prototype. Advances in 3D printing have opened up a new world.
</p>[<a href="http://www.3dsystems.com/30-years-innovation" rel="nofollow">source</a>]<br>[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:MakerBot_Replicator_2.jpg" rel="nofollow">image source</a>]
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 13 -->
          <article id="slide-z24oAg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 In 2013, Gartner started tracking the under $100,000 printer market – it’s relatively new, and demand is estimated to double between 2014 and 2015. Rapid quality and better performance are driving this demand.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 14 -->
          <article id="slide-yb96rz">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 Gartner Research projects enterprise-quality 3D printers will cost under $2000 by 2016.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://www.gartner.com/newsroom/id/2388415" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 15 -->
          <article id="slide-ye4Dxz">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	We’re already seeing hobbyist models that are a tenth of the price of early Makerbots.
</p>[<a href="http://static.makerwise.com/static/img/3d-printer/orig/287/makibox-a6-lt-05.jpg" rel="nofollow">image source</a>]
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 16 -->
          <article id="slide-g9EdNg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	Prices are declining, and both consumers and enterprise are buying. Projections suggest that the 3D printer market could reach $5.7 billion by 2017.
</p>
<p>
	These adoption trends are often compared to the PC revolution of the 1990s.
</p>[<a href="http://www.gartner.com/newsroom/id/2600115" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 17 -->
          <article id="slide-zV7Mdy">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 3D printing has changed form prototyping. For a functional prototype, you have to build the guts. Single-board computers, microcontrollers, and wifi-enabled development boards have changed made functional prototyping fast and accessible, even for a beginner.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 18 -->
          <article id="slide-yvAnlz">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	    I’m pretty excited about this. If you’ve never checked out Octopart, you should. It’s a search engine devoted to component pricing. When I told them I was giving this talk, we got excited about the idea of a Consumer Price Index (CPI) for common components. Standardizing a basket proved impractical, but here’s the first edition of the Octopart Microcontroller Price Index. It shows average pricing trends for the top thousand microcontrollers.
</p>
<p>
	    The average price of a <strong>single microcontroller (blue)</strong> has dropped, <strong>volume pricing (red)</strong> has gone up slightly.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://octopart.com/blog/archives/2014/5/announcing-the-octopart-microcontroller-price-index" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
