          <!-- slide 45 -->
          <article id="slide-yL7Dqz">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	  In 2012, there were 8.7 billion connected objects globally. That was .6% of the ‘things' in the world. This number is projected to hit 50 billion by 2020. And that’s still only 2.7% of the things in the world.
</p>
<p>
	  These connections will be dominated by two sectors: consumer electronics (including cameras, music players and TVs) and intelligent buildings (e.g. security and HVAC systems).
</p>
<p>
	 Between them they will account for almost 70% of the total.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://www.juniperresearch.com/viewpressrelease.php?pr=429" rel="nofollow">source</a>]<br>
	[<a href="http://blog.cytalk.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/machina-chart.jpg" rel="nofollow">source</a>]<br>
	[<a href="http://www.juniperresearch.com/viewpressrelease.php?pr=344" rel="nofollow">source</a>]<br>
	[<a href="https://machinaresearch.com/news/press-release-machine-to-machine-connections-to-hit-18-billion-in-2022-generating-usd13-trillion-revenue/" rel="nofollow">source</a>]<br>
	[<a href="http://newsroom.cisco.com/feature-content?articleId=1208342" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
