          <article id="slide-zYEYrz">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	People are paying attention.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 47 -->
          <article id="slide-XWE19y">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 And people are paying money. Here we have projections of global revenues generated from smart home services, including entertainment.
</p>[<a href="http://www.alliedmarketresearch.com/smart-home-automated-building-market" rel="nofollow">source</a>]<br>[<a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/home/how-to-protect-your-fancy-new-connected-home-from-savvy-hackers/" rel="nofollow">image source</a>]
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 48 -->
          <article id="slide-XZEWOg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 There’s one final subset of the hardware ecosystem to briefly touch on: wearables, a popular subset of connected devices.
</p>
<p>
	 As Mary Meeker noted in her Internet Trends 2013 talk, they’re coming on stronger than we normally see in the traditional 10-year tech cycle. I think one of the reasons for that is the current emphasis on UX and UI, and creating a beautiful experience out of the box.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://www.kpcb.com/insights/2013-internet-trends" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 49 -->
          <article id="slide-g885Rg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	 What you see here is the sale of wearable devices, and the increasing percentage of those devices with embedded cellular capabilities. The installed base of connected appliances in Smart Homes will beat the 10 million mark by 2017, rising from 4 million in 2013.
</p>
<p>
	 Adoption is happening much more quickly in wearables than in the connected home, because they are comparatively low friction, and are offered by trusted brands. Cost is also a factor. I also think that the killer experience for the connected home hasn't been created yet.
</p>
<p>
	 [<a href="http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/collateral/service-provider/visual-networking-index-vni/white_paper_c11-520862.html" rel="nofollow">source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 50 -->
          <article id="slide-XpK1Zg">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	  Make no mistake about it:
</p>
<p>
	  hardware is still hard.
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 51 -->
          <article id="slide-Xw7nZX">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	   But the trends we’re seeing across the ecosystem, in protoyping, manufacturing, and fundraising – they all indicate that it’s getting progressively easier to get from that idea on a napkin to a space on the shelf.
</p>
<p>
	  [image source: <em>The Hardware Startup: Building Your Product, Business, and Brand</em> — forthcoming book by Renee DiResta and Nick Pinkston]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
          <!-- slide 52 -->
          <article id="slide-y0B63X">

            <div class="slide layout-middle contains-1 contains-heading has-heading all- has-bg-image">
              <div class="slide-inner-wrap">
                <div class="slide-inner">
                  <div class="slide-content">
                      <div class="e e-1 e-heading">
                        <h1 class="heading">
  
</h1>

                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>


            <aside class="narrative">
                <p>
	   Marc Andreessen once said, “Six decades into the computer revolution, four decades since the invention of the microprocessor, and two decades into the rise of the modern Internet, all of the technology required to transform industries through software finally works and can be widely delivered at global scale.”
</p>
<p>
	   And while it may yet be early to make the same claim about hardware, the hardware revolution is happening. Which means that we’re in for some truly exciting developments, as today’s creators leverage the power of software and the promise of hardware, and bring new and compelling connected devices into the world.
</p>
<p>
	   Thank you.
</p>
<p>
	[<a href="http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424053111903480904576512250915629460" rel="nofollow">quote source</a>]
</p>
            </aside>
          </article>
      </div>

